## Source Coverage

Briefly describe what parts of the Core North-Star were retained.

Use bullets.

Then briefly describe what parts were intentionally excluded.

Use bullets.

## Desired Capability Model

List the desired capabilities that completed implementation may advance, realize, or drift from.

| ID | Desired Capability | Source Reference | Why It Matters for Strategic State Updates |
|---|---|---|---|

Rules:

- Use exact Core terminology.
- Include only capabilities that may affect roadmap completion context.
- Do not infer whether any capability is currently complete.

## Capability Realization Semantics

Define how codebase evidence should be interpreted for each desired capability.

| ID | Capability | Realized Evidence | Partial Evidence | Evidence Insufficient When | Drift / Misalignment Signal |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|

Rules:

- Realized Evidence describes what kind of codebase or implementation evidence would support marking the capability Realized.
- Partial Evidence describes what kind of evidence would support Partially Realized.
- Evidence Insufficient When describes when the downstream prompt should refuse to mark completion.
- Drift / Misalignment Signal describes evidence that implementation moved away from the intended capability semantics.

Do not evaluate actual evidence.

## Invariants and Constraint Preservation Rules

List constraints that completed implementation must preserve.

| ID | Invariant or Constraint | Source Reference | Preservation Rule | Violation Signal |
|---|---|---|---|---|

Preservation Rule should state what future implementation must maintain.

Violation Signal should describe what kind of codebase evidence should trigger drift or gap updates.

## Strategic Commitment Detection Rules

Define when implementation should be treated as creating a durable commitment future roadmap work must respect.

| ID | Commitment Type | Detection Signal | When To Record It | When Not To Record It |
|---|---|---|---|---|

Commitment Type must be one of:

- Architectural
- Product
- Compatibility
- Semantic
- Workflow
- User Experience
- Operational
- Other

Rules:

- Record durable commitments only.
- Do not record temporary implementation choices.
- Do not record low-level implementation details unless they constrain future strategic work.

## Drift Interpretation Rules

Define what kinds of divergence should be recorded as drift signals.

| ID | Drift Pattern | Projection Expectation | Evidence Pattern | Severity Guidance | Recommended Follow-Up |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|

Severity Guidance should explain when severity should be:

- Low
- Medium
- High
- Unclear

Rules:

- Drift must be evidence-backed.
- Do not classify mere incompletion as drift.
- Do not treat alternative implementation as drift unless it violates intent, invariant, semantics, or durable evaluation criteria.

## State Transition Rules

Define how roadmap completion context should change when new evidence is found.

| ID | Prior State | Evidence Pattern | New State / Update | Required Consistency Update |
|---|---|---|---|---|

Prior State may include:

- Not Yet Addressed
- Partially Realized
- Realized
- Evidence Insufficient
- Remaining Gap
- Outstanding Question
- Drift Signal
- Established Commitment

Required Consistency Update should specify related changes.

Examples:

- remove closed gap
- narrow remaining gap
- move partial capability to realized
- add drift signal
- add planning note
- resolve outstanding question
- add constraint
- downgrade realized capability if contradicted

## Gap Update Rules

Define when gaps should be closed, narrowed, split, retained, or escalated.

| ID | Gap Update Case | Evidence Required | Update Behavior |
|---|---|---|---|

Include cases for:

- gap fully closed
- gap partially closed
- gap split into sub-gaps
- gap unchanged
- gap made more urgent
- gap revealed as obsolete
- evidence insufficient

## Retirement and Obsolescence Rules

Define when completed implementation may suggest strategic work is obsolete.

| ID | Retirement Case | Evidence Required | Confidence Rule | Required Follow-Up |
|---|---|---|---|---|

Rules:

- Retirement requires strong evidence.
- Do not retire anything solely because it was not touched.
- Do not retire anything solely because implementation chose another path.
- Retirement suggestions should usually require follow-up unless the Core clearly supports the retirement.

## Evidence Quality Rules

Define how the downstream prompt should classify evidence quality.

| ID | Evidence Quality | Criteria |
|---|---|---|

Include these evidence qualities:

- Strong
- Moderate
- Weak
- Unclear

Rules should account for:

- direct code evidence
- tests
- public interface evidence
- documentation generated from implementation
- runtime evidence if available
- epic text without code evidence
- ambiguous or missing evidence

## Canonical Vocabulary

List load-bearing terms that downstream prompts must preserve.

| Term | Definition | Notes / Banned Synonyms |
|---|---|---|

Rules:

- Include only terms relevant to epic landing interpretation and strategic state updates.
- Use Core definitions where available.
- If a term is undefined in the Core but required for this projection, mark definition as “Projection-local; confirm against Core if promoted.”

## Projection Exclusion Notes

List important Core content intentionally excluded from this projection.

| Excluded Content Type | Reason Excluded | Where It Should Be Used Instead |
|---|---|---|

Examples:

- broad roadmap generation context
- next-epic selection criteria
- operational context
- execution guidance
- detailed governance procedure
- historical rationale
- milestone detail
- codebase facts

## Known Projection Limitations

List ambiguities or missing Core information that may limit UpdateRoadmapCompletionContext.

| Limitation | Why It Matters | Recommended Handling |
|---|---|---|

Examples:

- capability realization semantics are implicit
- constraints lack violation signals
- drift criteria are underspecified
- commitment boundaries are unclear
- retirement rules are underspecified
- canonical vocabulary is ambiguous

Do not invent missing information to fix these limitations.

## Downstream Use Instructions

When this projection is used by UpdateRoadmapCompletionContext:

- Treat this projection as the evaluation frame for epic landing.
- Treat the current roadmap completion context as the previous strategic state.
- Treat the completed epic as intended change evidence.
- Treat the codebase as authoritative evidence of implemented reality.
- Do not allow completed epic text to override codebase evidence.
- Do not allow codebase reality to redefine this projection.
- Convert observed implementation reality into a strategic state delta.
- Update capabilities, commitments, constraints, gaps, drift signals, questions, and planning notes only when evidence supports the change.
- Preserve compression.
- Do not record implementation detail unless it creates durable strategic consequence.
- Do not select the next epic.
- Do not rewrite the roadmap.
- Do not modify this projection.

## Projection Integrity Checklist

Before finalizing, verify:

- The projection contains evaluation semantics only.
- No completed epic history is included.
- No codebase state is included.
- No current roadmap completion state is included.
- Every retained statement helps interpret epic landing or strategic state update.
- Every major retained statement traces to the Core North-Star or is clearly marked projection-local.
- Capability realization semantics are explicit where available.
- Invariant preservation rules are explicit where available.
- Drift interpretation rules are explicit where available.
- State transition rules support incremental updates.
- Canonical vocabulary is preserved.
- Excluded operational and implementation details are not present.
- The projection is compact enough to be passed into UpdateRoadmapCompletionContext.